   <titles>
      <title>3-Dimensional Orientation and Rotations</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The right hand orientation is closely related to what is called rotation about an oriented axis according to the right hand rule. </para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/RightHandRule.jpg"/>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>In the picture above the 
				<subordinate>
                     <hot>toroidal</hot>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>A torus looks like the surface of a donut or an inner tube</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </subordinate>
				object above 
					<subordinate>
                     <hot>rotates</hot>
                     <external.link href="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/~gepe/LinearAlgebraRn/Determinants/ims/RightHandRule.avi"
                                    target="new"
                                    type="animation">
                        <info xmlns="">
                           <para xmlns="Unit">
                              <para.body>View an animation of this rotation. You need to have an animation player capable of using the avi-file format.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </external.link>
                  </subordinate>
				in the direction of the arrows near "FCM". To identify this rotation as one according to the right hand rule we note: The axis of rotation is oriented by the displayed vector, call it <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                  </math>. Upon aligning the thumb of your right hand with <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                  </math>, your curled fingers point in the direction of the rotation.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The relationship between a "rotation according to the right hand rule" and the "right hand orientation" is obtained as follows.</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Choose any nonzero vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Let <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> be the result of rotating <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> through the angle of <math>
                           <latex>\pi/2</latex>
                        </math> according to the right hand rule.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Then the triple <math>
                           <latex>(\Vect{x},\Vect{y},\Vect{z})</latex>
                        </math> represents the right hand orientation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
